senses.sense: (archaic) simple past tense and past participle of owe
(ditransitive) To be under an obligation to give something back to someone or to perform some action for someone.
examples: I owe Kevin five bucks which he lent to me last week.
This time I'll cover for you, but now you owe me a favour.

senses.sense: (intransitive) To have debt; to be in debt.
(transitive) To have as a cause; used with to.
examples: The record owes its success to the outstanding guitar solos.

senses.sense: simple past tense and past participle of owe
A person who owes something, especially money.
third-person singular simple present indicative form of owe
Still to be paid; owed as a debt.

(by extension) A person seen as having owl-like characteristics, especially appearing wise or serious, or being nocturnally active.
(politics, uncommon) A politician with moderate views that are neither hawkish nor dovish.
Any of various nymphalid butterflies, especially in the genus Caligo, having large eyespots on the wings.
The realm or sphere of owls.
(Lancashire, Northern English dialectal) The alder tree.
(dated) A smuggler of sheep or wool.
(zoology) An abode or a haunt of owls.
One of a species of small owls, such as Athene noctua.
(historical) The smuggling of sheep or wool out of England.
(internet slang) A variation on planking in which a person is photographed or filmed squatting down in an unusual location.
A small, juvenile, or baby owl; owlet.
Resembling or characteristic of an owl.
In an owlish manner, especially with regard to looking.
The state or condition of being owlish.

Belonging to; possessed; acquired; proper to; property of; titled to; held in one's name; under/using the name of. Often marks a possessive determiner as reflexive, referring back to the subject of the clause or sentence.

examples: When we move into the new house, the kids will each have their own bedroom.

senses.sense: (transitive) To have rightful possession of (property, goods or capital); to have legal title to; to acquire a property or asset.
(transitive) To have recognized political sovereignty over a place, territory, as distinct from the ordinary connotation of property ownership.
examples: The United States owns Point Roberts by the terms of the Treaty of Oregon.

senses.sense: (transitive) To defeat or embarrass; to overwhelm.
examples: If he wins, he will own you.

senses.sense: (online gaming, slang) To defeat, dominate, or be above, also spelled pwn.
(transitive, computing, slang) To illicitly obtain superuser or root access to a computer system, thereby having access to all of the user files on that system; pwn.
(intransitive) To admit, concede, grant, allow, acknowledge, confess; not to deny.
(transitive) To proudly acknowledge; to not be ashamed or embarrassed of.

examples: to own one as a son

senses.sense: Something that can be owned; a commodity or item of property.
simple past tense and past participle of own

examples: The police recovered the stolen car and returned it to its owner.

senses.sense: (nautical, slang) The captain of a ship.
The state of having complete legal control of something; possession; proprietorship.

examples: The successful candidate will take ownership of all internal design projects.

senses.sense: The property of being one's own.
third-person singular simple present indicative form of own
(now chiefly regional, especially southern US, Caribbean, Singlish) (One's) self; used with a preceding possessive adjective to form a pronominal phrase.
(mineral) An orthorhombic-dipyramidal gray-white mineral containing antimony, bismuth, lead, silver, and sulfur.
